    "The eigenvalues of L(G) are denoted byµ 1 (G) ≥ • • • ≥ µ n-1 (G) ≥ µ n (G) = 0.In [8] it is proved that a graph is connected if and only if µ n-1 (G) > 0.",
    "This eigenvalue is called algebraic connectivity and is denoted by a(G).",
    "Fiedler also proved that the vertex connectivity is an upper bound for the algebraic connectivity of non-complete graphs.",
    "The signless Laplacian matrix of a graph G, denoted by Q(G), is obtained from the sum of the diagonal matrix and the adjacency matrix, Q(G) = D(G) + A(G).",
    "The characteristic polynomial of this matrix Q is denoted by p Q (λ), and its eigenvalues (also known as Q-eigenvalues) are denoted by q 1 (G) ≥ q 2 (G) ≥ • • • ≥ q n (G), with q 1 (G) being the largest of them, known as the index of Q(G) or spectral radius of the signless Laplacian matrix."
